            <a name="678529"></a>
            
	<div valign="top" class="content-listimage">

            
            <div class="size11 darkgray content-meta">
                <div class="floatleft" style="margin-top:-2px; margin-right:10px"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111100413/http://it.toolbox.com/people/unknownuser/"><div class="userimage-defaulttiny"></div></a>
</div>


<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111100413/http://it.toolbox.com/people/unknownuser/" class="size11">Unknown User</a>

<!---->

				
<span class="pubdate size11 darkgray" title="2003-11-20 14:10:00Z">Nov 20, 2003</span>
                
                

            </div>
			<span class="anthracite size13" contentbodystyle="Anthracite">Well, let's see.  We've met a cast of characters.  We've got a wireless device in a secure data center.  The particular make and model has an approxamate range of about 300 feet. We've got an intern who apparently parks next to the back wall, or as close to it as he can get.  Said intern has just been busted for illegal access of a secure internet (rut roh) and is in debt up to his eyebrows for access time with Link-9.  Our cast of company characters seem clean (excepting Jeremy the intern)and likeable.  



We know that the wireless point didn't put itself in the data center.  The back door requires someone inside to open it.  It may or may not alarm when opened, the Chief didn't say.  Still, to open it, you need someone inside.  That could be a willing participant or just some one who got scammed.  



/* Aside: reminds me of the Monty Python Burglar skit.  */



If it was someone who got scammed, then some education is in store for all employees.



If it was a data center employee, somebody's looking at termination and possibly some Time.  Conspiracy to defraud is a bad thing.  So is Theft of Services.



It could have been a simple, after hours B &amp; E.  Basicly a case of slipping a shim in between the door and its jam and popping the lock.  But the person would have needed inside knowledge of the interior data center layout and the data center network configuration to know where to tie the wireless point in.  Especially considering the time syncing.  So that would probably rule out a black-bag team and indicate an employee.  If Jeremy gives up their name as the sole accomplice then he has something to fear from his new business partners, as he is protecting them.



Jeremy mentioned that the person(s) who helped him and his partner had overcome some obstacles for them.  This implies that there is considerably more going on than has been uncovered thus far.  Specifically; he said, "Yes. They wanted in on our business. They helped us get around a lot of the problems we had once our colo provider cut us off. "  Soooo then, this unknown helpmate wanted a piece of their business and was providing illegal network access in return for it.  Jeremy better squirm.  Jeremy is looking at some very serious Time.  Ask Mitnick.  Ask the two guys who just got busted for hacking Lowe's wireless system and going after credit card numbers.  



I wonder how many other companies in that area have experienced this same problem recently.



One thought out of left field: how clean is Link-9?





</span>
		</div>
           
    <div class="spacer"></div>

    <div class="rule-gray"></div>
    <div class="spacer-small"></div>

    
            <a name="678532"></a>
            
	<div valign="top" class="content-listimage">

            
